Holidays 2022 vs. Holidays 2021 [SWIPE➡️] Last year at this time I prayed so hard every day that we’d have our rainbow baby here for the next holiday season. Seeing my boys finally wearing these matching outfits after I purchased this sweatshirt before our miscarriages in 2021 (thankfully it still fits!!) is pure magic and a true miracle🥹

If you’re going through the hell of holiday season while struggling through TTC or baby loss, I see you and know how shitty it feels💔Promise there is light at the end of the tunnel and for now just do your best to take care of you and tune the rest out. Last year I took a total social media hiatus for 3 months during the holidays/new year to avoid possible triggers and it was the best decision I could have made for my mental health.

Did you ever have a holiday season of struggling through TTC (trying to conceive) or baby loss when everyone around you seemed happily pregnant or with growing families? How did you get through it?

💋Kissing this transformational year goodbye.. On January 1 2022 I pulled myself out of eating and drinking my way through the holidays no longer pregnant to channeling my energy ✨into manifesting our rainbow baby. I began @gabbybernstein manifestation challenge and one week in took a positive pregnancy test. To most - a baby! To loss mamas- promising but scary…! Each day I diligently followed the tasks and meditations, resisting projections of my past and reaching for hope towards my future. 

One by one the pieces fell into place just like in the manifestation: from the promising HCG numbers that I checked over and over on the online portal to the moment our RE said (in real life not just my dreams!) “There’s the heartbeat and baby is measuring perfect” 🥹

While I don’t know for sure if I manifested our pregnancy, I do believe that the universe has its way of lining up the events of our lives in a meaningful order. No, not everything “happens for a reason” 🤦🏻‍♀️because that doesn’t feel right through grief, but maybe, just maybe, we can trust that no matter how the year ends, there’s a meaningful plan in store for our future. 💫

📷: @kate_leichhardt

I’m FINALLY in labor. I think. It’s 3:01pm on September 27 and I’m 40 weeks and 6 days pregnant. My induction is scheduled for tomorrow and I just got back from another appointment with the midwife who did a “stretch and sweep” to get me to 5cm dilated. I lost a mucous plug and have been having contractions, but this happened last week after a stretch and ended up fizzling. Of course today I had my “bloody show” after an hour of curb walking so this feel promising, but it’s not over till it’s over.

Finally piecing together my birth story in a blog post! This was the beginning of the end of what felt like the longest road to get to our 🌈 baby!

The emotions and trauma of what had come before at that hospital were intense and a lot to get through during birth. I did not expect that but it makes sense looking back. Thankfully hypnobirthing techniques and nitrous oxide (was great for anxiety!) plus an awesome support team helped.

What would you like to see in this blog post? Is there anything you love being included in birth stories? Any questions you have about unmedicated hospital births or birth after loss? Comment here or send me a DM and I’ll make sure to include it in my birth story blog post coming soon!

🪐how I ended up arriving at the hospital 7 cm dilated

When the dawn breaks after those long nights, I hope you remember that just like the sun rises again, there will be brighter days ahead. Days when your bones won’t ache with exhaustion and you’ll feel like yourself again. Days when it’ll all be a messy blur, but one that you wouldn’t rewrite if you got the chance. Chag Sameach - Happy Passover from Mexico 👋🏻 🌴Not going to lie… we did not quite realize the timing when we planned this trip forever ago. I felt a little guilty when it occurred to me that we’d miss the big family celebrations and holiday traditions, but now that we’re here it makes sense as a unique way to observe this year.

If you’re not familiar with Pesach, or “Passover” it’s when Jews celebrate freedom from slavery and new beginnings. Seems fitting to be celebrating the end of one chapter for us - the bittersweet road to our little family and beginning of the next- enjoying this adventure called life together.

Reflecting on sweet memories with those who have passed who my boys are named after who loved this holiday and celebrated it with such JOY and ZEST. I see them so much in these two every day and it brings me great pleasure.

I’m sure next year we’ll be back to tasting the “maror” and reciting the four questions, but for now, I am going to soak up this extra special first Pesach as a family of four 🤍✨

A blow to the belly, a tear down the cheek, all with you watching, wondering and needing me to guide your innocent soul on this journey of growing up.

Your rosy view of the world is so pure, so joyful, how can I be the one to spoil that? toss and turn wondering what the right answers are.

This is motherhood in America. 💔

Do you have trips planned or hope to plan trips with kids?

In all our travels with one, and now two, we’ve both overpacked 😵‍💫and underpacked. Neither are ideal. So here are my tips to avoid both:

🌴DO pack a change of clothes for yourself and all kids in carry on. I’ve been covered in puke down to my undies without them and regretted it immensely 🤪

🌴DO bring an iPad with kids at an age to use it. You can always say no iPad time, but you can’t make one appear on that unexpected cancelled flight layover

🌴DO pack lots of snacks - there’s never enough

🌴DO bring car seats- you can’t always trust the rental company ones

🌴DO pack sleep essentials. Sleep sack, portable sound machine, lovey or whatever makes it similar to your home environment. Not necessary but we also love portable blackout shades and slumber pod if room sharing

🌴DO pack feeding essentials and supplements. Bottles/water cups/water bottles etc. we’ve forgotten the water bottle and it’s devastating 🤪. I also brought disposable bibs this time and love

🌴DO bring a carrier if your little is small enough to use one they’re great for naps on the go, running through the airport and other hands free stuff

🌴DO pack water safety items like life vests if you’ll need them (can’t trust rental companies to have right sizes)

❌DONT bring bulky stuff that you can easily rent. We’ve used domestic and intl rental companies for larger essentials. They can be pricey tho so best for only big items

❌DONT bring stuff your destination has. Check with your rental company, rental host or hotel for what they may be able to provide! We’ve gotten great pack and plays, high chairs, etc this way!

❌DONT bring anything consumable you can easily get while there. Our intl trip I brought way more than other domestic trips down the street from grocery/convenience stores. 

❌DONT bring anything you can easily ship. I will Amazon some consumable stuff to our domestic destinations when possible or sent a coterie diaper order there a couple trips

❌DONT bring anything you can borrow. When we visit family, we have ended up borrowing bassinets, bouncers, strollers from their neighbors and friends!

Okay what did I miss?!

Here’s how I practice mindfulness with my kids!🍃

As a mama, teacher and yoga teacher I have many favorites for encouraging mindfulness from early on… including infancy!

Blowing a dandelion is a big fave! A great way for kiddos to connect with the breath even as babies.

Baking and cooking is a great way to encourage mindful eating with older kiddos so they can use all 5 senses to engage with the food!

Food before one is:

👅 For oral development
✋🏻 For sensory processing
🦠 For allergy detection
💩 For gut micro biome building
👂 For language development

…and so much more!

Saying food is “just for fun” between 6-12 months may cause caregivers to 
🚫delay solids unnecessarily too long
🚫not prioritize offering a developmentally appropriate number of meals per day
🚫Ignore feeding red flags/issues that could be detected and resolved early 

Both of my babes worked with SLPs on feeding issues and GI doctors on food allergies and I learned how important these early days are to their long term feeding success! Breastmilk and formula should still be a primary source of calories during this phase, but it doesn’t mean that the introduction of solids is ONLY for fun though it can be fun too!🍌🍉🍑🍏🥑! 

What’s been the biggest struggle to introducing solids with your kids? For me it’s always the meal prep and making sure I have a variety of meals each week!

9 MONTHS IN // 9 MONTHS OUT 🫶🏼 can’t resist a little fun with this sweet milestone. The first year is a wild ride, but I wouldn’t trade it for anything.

3 (equipment free!) Core Exercises for Pregnancy and Postpartum 💪🏽

💫Tiny hip circles: Come to all fours and extend one leg back and flexed while keeping your hand on your hip to help activate your abdominals. Your shin can be at an angle or straight for more of a challenge. Pretend you’re tracing circles on the back wall with your foot.

💫Thread the needles: from the same position, leave your foot up or place it down. Reach your top hand up towards the ceiling then down under your bottom armpit. 

💫Rainbow kicks: Come to all fours and keep your chest and hips square to the floor. Extend one leg out towards the corner of your mat then lifting in an arc shape to tap down on the opposite side.

For more pregnancy and postpartum exercises follow @helenekusmanyoga where I’ll be sharing more of my favorites to use both with clients and for my own strengthening/recovery!

I’ve been pumping between both kids for 15+ months and the single thing that’s saved me the MOST milk is remembering that breastmilk can stay at room temp 🌡️ for 4 hours safely. If I’m stuck without a cooler or find that my milk didn’t stay cool enough😳 (like it did at derby despite my best efforts)… I count the hours and if it’s only been 4 I don’t toss it. This is per the CDC and I won’t advise otherwise but have heard from reliable sources that up to 6 is acceptable under clean circumstances. I had some breastfeeding related OCD/anxiety with my first, so I try to let go of obsessing this time around, but sure don’t want to toss any perfectly good milk!

We’ve taken both boys (4 years and 10 months) to Florida, Mexico and DC several times, but this weeks flight to Denver was one of the smoothest 🙌🏻Here’s what we did:

✈️Took a super early flight which was rough at first but we got ahead of them being overtired
✈️Hid a bunch of our small baby toys and electronic toys for a week so they’d be novel for Graham
✈️Bought these suction fidget spinners and they kept both boys busy
✈️Brought different snacks than usual for both boys for Graham some sweet potato puff sticks which I’m now obsessed with!
✈️Allow unlimited snacks for Harper which avoids a battle and makes travel days easier
✈️Allow unlimited iPad time for Harper and even let Graham watch with him some if nothing else is keeping him happy
✈️Let Harper pick a special treat at the airport shop which gets him excited and gives him some power/decision making
✈️Bring sticker and tape activity books for Harper

…and most important lower MY expectations for the day. Our last flight was ROUGH and I was thinking maybe it was their current ages but its just always hit or miss especially with out of control logistics. Lowering my expectations and expecting a shit show but hoping for the best always seems to help me get through the day less stressed 🙃which in turn helps the boys be leased stressed with calmer energy!

#worldbreastfeedingweek has me reflecting on the most important lesson I’ve learned from feeding babies: When you do what works for your family, you can’t go wrong 👊🏻. 

With Harper I set a goal of breastfeeding for a year. Tongue ties, failure to thrive and undiagnosed food protein allergies led to exclusively pumping then weaning at 6 months with a lot of guilt and disappointment. I wish I knew then what I knew now and could have felt proud of myself for my effort, but not put so much of my worth as a mom in how I fed my baby. 

Fast forward to Graham. Our journey of multiple losses and a challenging pregnancy put perspective on breastfeeding. Plus I had learned my lesson to be gentle with myself after having had PPA/PPD with Harper. There was no room for shame or guilt. I breastfed through a hospital stay where I was not allowed to feed him and didn’t have a pump for a while, a tongue tie that we didn’t end up revising, food protein allergies that had me on an allergen free restrictive diet for 6 months plus all of the usual challenges that breastfeeding comes along with. 

This time around I did it because it brought me joy and not because of any pressure on myself like before. I surprised myself that breastfeeding has affected my mental health this time, but positively. It’s provided a daily time connect w my body and baby that exclusive pumping just didn’t do for me last time around. The cool part is I’ve set no goals and don’t plan to.

Each day I reevaluate what’s working for our family and go from there. Does outside pressure ever creep in? Of course. I’m human and don’t wear blinders. Others opinions one way or another certainly cross my mind. But ultimately each day I come back to the same thought: what’s working for our family? What’s working for me? And that gives me all that I need to move along this journey of motherhood with a little bit of confidence and a lot of joy 🦋🤍

Working out postpartum feels confusing at times. What if I don’t care about “bouncing back?” but still really, really, want to achieve my fitness goals? There is no guilt or shame in wanting to prioritize yourself during this season. Find your why, and watch how it shifts your motivation and entire outlook 💪🏽⚡️👶🏻

Want to teach mindful eating to little ones? Here are a few things that I don’t by any means do perfectly, but try to do when it comes to sharing this practice with my kids.

1️⃣Let them select their food (with guidance). Choosing veggies? Let them pick out the ones that look good or which veggies they want to eat/cook with that week

2️⃣Invite them to help in the kitchen. Even if it’s just a matter of pushing the salad spinner or washing/drying some produce

3️⃣Let them choose what they eat on their plate. This is a challenge for me that I am always working on. My goal is to offer at least one thing I know will be a win and several other things to try and strive to send the message that he can eat whatever and how much he wants

I’m almost a year postpartum and these pre-baby jeans are not in my Fall wardrobe! After baby number 1 at first I felt like it was a waste of money to buy a pair of jeans that fit in case I ended up back in the old size. I DID end up back in some (not all) of my old pants but not for over a year so I was glad I had those jeans and am glad I do this time around as well. I’m in no rush to get back into my old pants. If I ever do, great! If I don’t, that’s ok too. I’m so over the pressure to “snap back” and just want to feel my best and wear clothes that make me feel secure and confident 🙌🏻. Talking about mindfulness this week on the @pedsdoctalk podcast has me reflecting on my favorite way to connect mindfully with our 4 year old lately. Not just letting him help in the kitchen, but actually allowing him to be creative 🌀and get messy. 

He wanted to make fire truck 🚒cookies so instead of our usual premade cookie dough we kneaded, rolled and stamped our little trucks together, mixing food coloring and icing and sprinkling them per his idea. It’s not realistic to allow kids to come up with cooking/baking creations all the time, but even allowing simple decisions like chocolate chip muffins or blueberry muffins? Plain pancakes or cinnamon pancakes? Is a nice way to foster mindful cooking/eating from an early age. 

Plus does it get any better than connecting with your 🖐🏻5 senses to encourage mindfulness than the smell and feel of sugar cookie dough? How do you feel about letting your kids get messy and creative in the kitchen? 

Follow @helenekusman for more mindfulness tips!

Did you bring the iPad? No did you? 🫠🫠🫠

Our conversation Thursday when we left on this trip. We remembered everything but our biggest tool for a smooth trip with the kids…

We keep the iPad in a box on top of our closet and only pull it out, charge and download stuff on it for trips so it can be easy to forget being out of sight.

But we both forgot it and thought we’d be doomed. We were pleasantly surprised on the way here that it was TOTALLY FINE. I didn’t know how we’d fill the time but a few sugary treats, coloring and looking out the window seemed to do the trick.

TBD on the way back… we are about to head home!

Positive test, heartbeat, viability, full gestation, birth and now 1 year! All of these milestones have meant the world after our two losses before Graham. There was a time when I doubted our road to growing our family would ever make sense or be OK. I’ve shared this before, but even during/after birth, there was still part of me that was confused, fearful and traumatized. I will never forget the physical and emotional pain that is forever imprinted on my heart and soul. I will never forget the babies that I got to carry even for a short amount of time. But I am also for the first time truly accepting of all that happened without one bit of resentment or anger. I still think about how old those babies would be now and my heart will always long to meet them, but I thank God, the Universe and whatever angels watching over us allowed the stars to align to bring us this very special little boy. If there’s one thing these kids have taught me, it’s that the journey that is motherhood is rarely a straight line, but it sure is pretty darn magical. If you’re going through your own not so straight line right now, I’m sending you some extra love and strength… you can do this 🫶🏼

As a Jew, I am horrified by the mass slaughtering of Jewish people in Israel by the designated terrorist group Hamas and the antisemitic reactions that have rippled across the globe to follow. 

But it shouldn’t take a Jew to condemn the mass rape and torture of women, beheading of children, babies burned alive in their cribs and kidnapping of innocent civilians including the elderly. 

 Please know that am holding space for all innocent civilian lives being lost in both Israel and Gaza. I realize that there is much shared trauma and grief in both experiences. AND also realize my profound responsibility as a Jew, comprising only 0.2% of the worldwide population, to speak up on our people’s history of persecution and antisemitism in this critical moment.

If not us, then who? If not now, then when? That is the question us Jews ask ourselves generation after generation when it comes to the proud and often difficult sharing our history, hardship, perseverance, faith, traditions and legacy with the world.

When you see or hear antisemitism in all forms including the justification of the slaughtering of Jews, please see my face and hear my voice. Please remember that we are real people, real families, real humans who have stood by so many other humans and held their hands through their own fights and struggles. The calling for death and extermination of Jews has happened before and it’s happening again. Know that this is just as much about me and my babies as it is our brothers and sisters across the world.

SAVE for your new favorite🍁Fall recipe: Pumpkin Spice Smoothie! I shopped for all of the ingredients at @thefreshmarket which you can find in the full recipe below. #TheFreshMarketPartner This smoothie is super creamy thanks to my trick - pumpkin purée ice cubes! It’s one of my very favorite warming spice smoothies for this time of year, plus both of my kids love it too.

🎃Pumpkin Spice Smoothie
1 ripe banana
1 cup pumpkin purée frozen into ice cubes
1 cup nut milk - I used @elmhurst1925 cashew milk
2 tbsp nut butter- I used @georgiagrinders pecan
1 tsp pumpkin spice
🌀BLEND until creamy
Top with chopped pecans + enjoy!
